00:08.240 --> 00:12.160
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:27.940 --> 00:33.280
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

00:35.920 --> 00:37.620
And here are your hosts.

00:43.100 --> 00:51.760
This is Daryl Lane. Frederik Pohl knows science fiction as few other people do.
He's been an editor of science fiction books and magazines, an agent who's

00:51.760 --> 00:59.480
handled the biggest names in the field, and an author who's won numerous Hugo
and Nebula awards. With such a background, Pohl is uniquely qualified to comment

00:59.480 --> 01:06.600
on science fiction. One of the things that impresses him the most is the way
science fiction has changed and diversified since he began writing in the 1930s.

01:07.620 --> 01:14.660
Science fiction today is not only very different from what it was in the 30s,
it's very different from other kinds of science fiction today. One of the things

01:14.660 --> 01:21.920
that attracts me to science fiction is that there are so many different kinds of
it. There are books like the one I mentioned before, Dahlgren, which are not a

01:21.920 --> 01:30.160
bit like the ones by Doc Smith, the Skylark stories, the Lenzman stories, which
are not a bit like the ones by Ursula Le Guin, which are not a bit like the ones

01:30.160 --> 01:44.860
by Larry Niven, for example. And I think that science fiction is characterized
by variety. There are very few general statements you can make about science

01:44.860 --> 01:54.720
fiction. It isn't fiction about science. It isn't fiction about the future. It
isn't fiction about space travel. It's fiction which has to do more than

01:54.720 --> 02:06.160
anything else with change. Somebody asked Arthur Clarke once why he wrote
science fiction. And he said something like, because it's the only literature

02:06.160 --> 02:15.980
that concerns itself with reality. Pohl believes science fiction's emphasis on
change can be beneficial. I think anybody who reads science fiction is very

02:15.980 --> 02:27.700
likely to be overcome by future shock. Well, when the atomic bomb fell on
Hiroshima, there were only about 10,000 people in the world who understood what

02:27.700 --> 02:36.180
had happened. About 500 nuclear physicists and the rest were all science fiction
fans. And I think the same has been true about the space program and about many

02:36.180 --> 02:48.400
of the social developments of the last 20 or 30 years. And I think that if you
read enough science fiction, you begin to get a spectrum of the possible futures

02:48.400 --> 02:57.380
that lie ahead for all of us. And I think it's quite useful in the sense that it
lets you make decisions now about which ones of them you would like to avoid or

02:57.380 --> 03:09.720
which ones you would like to avert. And it helps you find ways of taking actions
now that will encourage the good ones and discourage the bad ones. But it's not

03:09.720 --> 03:22.280
just that. I think science fiction also has a good deal of entertainment of what
is to me an extremely pleasurable kind to offer. Since the days of the pulp

03:22.280 --> 03:31.060
magazines in the 1920s and 1930s, science fiction has been a separate category
of literature. Some readers have scorned it as shallower second class. Pohl

03:31.060 --> 03:37.880
believes that the book publishers are responsible for keeping science fiction
separate. He also disagrees with the notion that science fiction is in any way

03:37.880 --> 03:47.520
inferior. The publishing industry is responsible for that. And in some ways,
it's a bad thing. A lot of people in this world like to read books but are

03:47.520 --> 03:57.760
prejudiced against anything that has the word science fiction on it. As I think
it's... I've forgotten the person who wrote the poem. There's a little poem

03:57.760 --> 04:05.420
about it which says something like, If it's science fiction, I don't like it.
And if I like it, it can't possibly be science fiction. Because there are a

04:05.420 --> 04:13.780
great many science fiction novels that everybody loves. They just don't admit
they're science fiction. The Great New World in 1984. And so on. Finally, Pohl

04:13.780 --> 04:23.480
believes that science fiction is uniquely qualified to treat any possible
subject matter. I think science fiction has special qualifications to act as a

04:23.480 --> 04:32.180
vehicle for discussing anything that affects the human being. It's a way of
looking at the human race from outside objectively. It's a way of... It's a sort

04:32.180 --> 04:41.660
of game-playing mechanism for seeing what would happen to human beings under
conditions that haven't occurred yet but are very possible. And I think that

04:41.660 --> 04:50.320
that's probably one of the strongest factors accounting for the continual growth
and interest in science fiction that seems to have been going on as long as I've

04:50.320 --> 04:50.740
been alive.

04:57.880 --> 05:05.680
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin
