05:05.680 --> 05:06.440
Odessa, Texas.

05:44.520 --> 05:48.520
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:04.600 --> 06:09.820
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

06:12.720 --> 06:14.180
And here are your hosts.

06:19.680 --> 06:28.680
This is Daryl Lane. Frederik Pohl has been a part of science fiction for almost
50 years. He knows the field as few others do, since he's been a fan, an author,

06:28.900 --> 06:38.580
an agent, and an editor. He recalls what got him interested in science fiction
back in the 1930s. Well, I think it was basically the adventure, the kind of

06:38.580 --> 06:48.500
science fiction that was being published around 1930, when I first got in touch
with it. When I first discovered that it existed, it was mostly space opera and

06:48.500 --> 06:59.400
gimmick stories and the stories about exciting, adventurous exploits all over
the galaxy. And that was in the middle of the Great Depression, and science

06:59.400 --> 07:07.600
fiction looked an awful lot better to me than the real world that I could see.
Pohl probably fulfilled a fantasy of his own when he became a science fiction

07:07.600 --> 07:18.820
editor when he was 19. I was lucky enough to fall into a job as a professional
magazine editor. When I was 19, I had asked an editor I knew, because I'd been

07:18.820 --> 07:28.460
trying to sell him stories without success, if he needed an assistant. And he
was kind enough not to laugh out loud. I didn't know at the time that not very

07:28.460 --> 07:35.720
many science fiction magazine editors could afford assistance. But he mentioned
to me another publishing company that was expanding and suggested I get in touch

07:35.720 --> 07:45.100
with them. So I did. It was popular publications, one of the biggest pulp houses
of the time. And they were expanding, and they gave me a job at $10 a week to

07:45.100 --> 07:54.740
edit two professional science fiction magazines. $10 wasn't so bad. They hired
other editors for nothing at the same time. Many of today's well-known writers

07:54.740 --> 08:03.600
published some of their early work with Pohl. Well, I published a lot of Isaac
Asimov stuff because we were close friends. A few of Robert A. Heinlein's

08:03.600 --> 08:14.600
stories that his primary market, John Campbell, for one reason or other, didn't
want to print. And Henry Kuttner and A.E. Van Vogt and Cleve Cartmill and L.

08:14.600 --> 08:25.300
Sprague de Camp. And most of the people who were writing at that time wound up in
my magazine, not always with their best stories. In fact, very often with their

08:25.300 --> 08:34.240
worst stories, because I wasn't paying very much. I had a budget of about half a
cent a word. In the 60s, Pohl edited Galaxy, one of the principal science

08:34.240 --> 08:41.960
fiction magazines of its era. Much of the best science fiction of that period
went through Pohl. His comments on how an editor deals with his authors are

08:41.960 --> 08:55.060
revealing. Writers are very diverse human beings. Some of them respond to long
letters of criticism and suggestions and patting on the back or beating over the

08:55.060 --> 09:07.440
head. And some of them do not want any outside influence at all. One of my
favorite writers told me early in our relationship that he was willing to have

09:07.440 --> 09:16.720
me buy some stories and reject others, but he didn't want to hear why. If I sent
it back, just send it back and say no. And not tell them what I didn't like

09:16.720 --> 09:25.460
about it, because that upset them. Other writers wanted to know in great detail
not only what I didn't like, but what I did like. And also there are some

09:25.460 --> 09:35.220
writers who are very responsive to money, and some to whom money means nothing
at all. Not that they are immune to it, but they don't want to think in those

09:35.220 --> 09:46.380
terms. And there are some writers who respond to a lot of personal attention,
and some who really want to be left alone. And I had to find out something about

09:46.380 --> 09:53.640
each writer to find out the best way to deal with them. One person Pohl
discovered and encouraged is one of science fiction's best-selling authors

09:53.640 --> 10:03.840
today, Larry Niven. I published his first story, which is a very short one, for
which he got a very short paycheck, and his next one was a little longer, and he

10:03.840 --> 10:12.560
got a little more, and the next one was quite a lot longer, and he got quite a
lot more. And Larry said that if it hadn't been for those three events in that

10:12.560 --> 10:22.620
order, he could not have gone on being a writer. So I take some pride in the
fact that I was instrumental in making it possible for him to devote his time to

10:22.620 --> 10:26.800
writing. For many reasons, we can be grateful Frederik Pohl was a science
fiction editor.

10:33.980 --> 10:41.860
