11:22.400 --> 11:26.280
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

11:42.780 --> 11:48.000
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

11:50.720 --> 11:52.320
And here are your hosts.

11:57.800 --> 12:06.460
This is Daryl Lane. One of the best known of all science fiction novels is a
collaboration between two authors, Frederik Pohl and Cyril Kornbluth. The novel

12:06.460 --> 12:15.520
is The Space Merchants. Published in 1951, the book is a clever social satire, a
form of writing not often found in science fiction. Huge advertising agencies

12:15.520 --> 12:24.240
run the United States. It's a classic example of extrapolation, one of the major
techniques of science fiction. Frederik Pohl had the original idea for the

12:24.240 --> 12:36.780
book. He recalls where it came from. When I was in the Army, in the Air Force in
World War II, I had some spare time on my hands in Italy, and I decided to write

12:36.780 --> 12:48.160
a novel. And the most interesting subject I could think of was the advertising
industry. So I wrote a whole novel about advertising. Very bad novel. After the

12:48.160 --> 12:54.460
war was over, I took it out and looked at it and realized that it was pretty
bad. And one of its great defects was that I didn't know anything about

12:54.460 --> 13:07.180
advertising. So I went to the New York Sunday Times and looked in the classified
section and found a couple of people advertising jobs in advertising and applied

13:07.180 --> 13:18.420
and got one of them and spent about three years as an advertising copywriter.
During that time, I looked over this old novel again and realized that it had

13:18.420 --> 13:28.140
many more faults than ignorance. And I burned it, and I had all the basic
information about advertising and no novel to put it in. So I thought of writing

13:28.140 --> 13:35.640
a science fiction novel. And it turned out to be The Space Merchant. Before the
war, Pohl had belonged to a science fiction group in New York called the

13:35.640 --> 13:43.400
Futurians. One member of that group was Cyril Kornbluth. He and Pohl had
collaborated before on science fiction stories. Pohl describes their method.

13:44.360 --> 13:54.820
Mostly what Cyril and I did was to, let's see, we wrote seven novels and a
number of short stories together. Generally speaking, what we did after the war,

13:55.140 --> 14:04.920
after the space merchants, and we began writing novels more often than short
stories. Cyril would come out to my house in Red Bank, New Jersey, where we kept

14:04.920 --> 14:15.540
the room for him with his own typewriter, and we'd sit around and talk for a
while and discuss general areas we were interested in writing about, maybe some

14:15.540 --> 14:25.100
characters. And then we'd flip a coin, and the loser would go up to the third
floor and write the first four pages. And he'd come down and say, you're on, and

14:25.100 --> 14:34.460
the other person would go up and write the next four pages. And if you do that
about 25 or 30 times, you have the rough draft of a complete novel. Everything

14:34.460 --> 14:42.580
got radically rewritten after that, because the rough draft was pretty rough,
but structurally it was all there. Kornbluth helped Pohl finish the space

14:42.580 --> 14:56.260
merchants. Cyril Kornbluth was a close friend of mine. We'd collaborated before
the war, before we both went into service. And after I'd written about a third

14:56.260 --> 15:07.960
of it, because the magazine editor wanted it in a hurry, I asked Cyril if he
wanted to help me with it, and he and I collaborated on it from that on. At the

15:07.960 --> 15:15.940
end of The Space Merchants, the protagonist, Mitch Courtenay, leaves an Earth
which is totally disgusting. There is no individual freedom. Food and energy are

15:15.940 --> 15:26.140
strictly rationed. Mitch heads for Venus with the idea of starting fresh, but
the ending is ambiguous. Is it hopeful or not? I left it ambiguous partly

15:26.140 --> 15:37.180
because I wasn't feeling very positive at the time. The novel was written in
1952 and thereabouts, which was a pretty grimy period in the history of this

15:37.180 --> 15:48.440
country. It was the McCarthy years and the Cold War years, and things did not
look too, they didn't look even as good as they do now, as a matter of fact. So

15:48.440 --> 15:56.760
I wasn't feeling optimistic. I didn't mean to foreclose the possibility of a
happy ending. Actually, the novel had two endings. There was a different ending

15:56.760 --> 16:06.720
in the magazine version. More upbeat, but less organically related to the rest
of the novel. It was put in at the insistence of the magazine editor.

