17:06.000 --> 17:11.000
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

17:29.720 --> 17:35.100
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

17:37.800 --> 17:39.400
And here are your hosts.

17:44.300 --> 17:52.980
This is David Carson. And Daryl Lane. In 1978, Frederik Pohl won a rare double
honor in science fiction. It was in that year his book Gateway won both the Hugo

17:52.980 --> 18:00.380
and Nebula Awards as the best science fiction novel of the year. The Nebula is
voted on by other science fiction writers, so Pohl's peers had high praise for

18:00.380 --> 18:07.640
the book. And the Hugo results from the votes of science fiction fans and
readers, so they also thought Pohl's novel to be exceptional. Both groups have

18:07.640 --> 18:14.600
good reason to think Gateway was something special. It's an exciting narrative
set against the background of a superior alien civilization. But the twist in

18:14.600 --> 18:21.360
Gateway is that the aliens, called the Heechee, have vanished. Humans have
discovered some of their abandoned technology, though. And that technology is

18:21.360 --> 18:29.460
impressive, but dangerous. Humans find portals or gates in the fabric of space,
and special Heechee ships nearby which can travel through those gates to various

18:29.460 --> 18:36.680
places around the universe. But the daring few who travel in the Heechee ships
usually don't know where they'll end up, or what they'll find when they arrive,

18:36.800 --> 18:45.120
or if they'll get back. But for those who return, the rewards can be enormous.
They usually arrive with fabulous Heechee artifacts, remnants of the superior

18:45.120 --> 18:53.580
Heechee technology, which make the travelers rich. Right. Sort of a cosmic
jackpot with a large risk involved. Pohl offers some of the reasons why Gateway

18:53.580 --> 19:04.560
turned out so well. Well, one of the big things in Gateway was that I was under
no pressure from anyone but myself to do it the way I thought it should be done.

19:05.040 --> 19:15.180
I had my publisher at that time, a principal publisher, was a man named Ian
Ballantine, who offered me a contract with a substantial advance to write a novel

19:15.180 --> 19:25.360
without saying what the novel was going to be, and without imposing any deadline
on when I had to deliver it. So I didn't have to discuss it with an editor ahead

19:25.360 --> 19:35.420
of time or write an outline and limit myself and the opportunities I could take.
And I didn't have the pressure of getting it delivered at a specific date to

19:35.420 --> 19:47.400
make me rush it through. And actually, it took me, I think, six years from the
time I signed the contract until I delivered it, and I had been mulling it over

19:47.400 --> 20:01.920
for several years before that. All in all, I think the book was something like
ten years in the gestation. And also, it's not possible for a writer to produce

20:01.920 --> 20:12.340
at the same level all the time. I don't know why. There are times when I write
better than others. I can't relate them to any outside influence or to my

20:12.340 --> 20:21.400
resolution to do well or anything like that. I just know that sometimes it comes
out better than other times, and Gateway, I think, is one of the times when it

20:21.400 --> 20:22.260
came out very well.

20:27.860 --> 20:38.020
The response to Gateway was strong enough to convince Pohl to write a sequel,
Beyond the Blue Event Horizon. I wasn't too hard to convince, but I did not have

20:38.020 --> 20:48.200
any such plan. I know that Gateway leaves a lot of questions unanswered and
suggests a lot of things that are not made explicit in the novel. And I did all

20:48.200 --> 20:56.780
that on purpose, but not for the sake of preparing the way for a sequel,
but just because I think that's a characteristic of

20:56.780 --> 21:06.940
a lot of good science fiction. When you finish the story, you think of things
that let you write your own stories after it. I mean, that's the sort of thing

21:06.940 --> 21:17.200
that Arthur Clarke does very well. And I think I try to do it whenever I can.
And it just turned out that there was a lot of public pressure to write a

21:17.200 --> 21:25.900
sequel. Beyond the Blue Event Horizon answers many of the questions about the
Heechee that Gateway raised. And in that book, mankind even discovers what is

21:25.900 --> 21:33.000
probably the last surviving Heechee, though it's found living in a symbiotic
relationship with a huge machine. Pohl resolved many of the questions about the

21:33.000 --> 21:40.600
Heechee technology and revealed more about what had happened to the vanished
Heechee civilization. But there are still questions about the Heechee not answered

21:40.600 --> 21:47.880
in Beyond the Blue Event Horizon. We asked Pohl about a sequel to that book.
There's also been public pressure to write another sequel, and I'm just about to

21:47.880 --> 21:52.520
sign a contract to do that, but I swear I had no such intention when I finished
Beyond the Blue Event Horizon.

