23:12.600 --> 23:16.500
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:32.520 --> 23:37.800
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and
fantasy.

23:40.500 --> 23:42.140
And here are your hosts.

23:47.240 --> 23:55.140
This is Daryl Lane. And David Carson. Frederik Pohl writes different kinds of
science fiction. All of it exciting. He's written action-packed space opera,

23:55.320 --> 24:03.160
like the Starchild trilogy he did with Jack Williamson, and some of his more
recent work, like Gateway, fall into that category. But Pohl also creates

24:03.160 --> 24:10.140
thoughtful science fiction with the emphasis on social comment. It's just as
fascinating in its own way. The Space Merchants is the best example of that

24:10.140 --> 24:20.500
type. Yes, that book goes back to the 50s, but recently he's written two fine
novels with social emphasis, Jem and Man Plus. Published in 1976, Man Plus

24:20.500 --> 24:29.260
depicts the world in turmoil, with political intrigue, international mistrust,
and the threat of nuclear devastation. Very negative picture. Pohl's suggested

24:29.260 --> 24:37.800
solution is to get man off the Earth to Mars. Pohl envisions a combination of
man and machine, a cyborg, adapting to the red planet and becoming native to

24:37.800 --> 24:52.240
that planet. I didn't make up the cyborg. It was, the term and the concept was
invented by two Air Force or NASA, I've forgotten which researchers, in 1958 or

24:52.240 --> 25:02.840
thereabouts. And it's been used widely in a lot of places, but I didn't make it
up. I think that we already see cyborgs in the sense that a lot of people have

25:02.840 --> 25:14.620
mechanical parts keeping them alive, pacemakers and artificial plastic veins and
arteries and so on. Not to mention things like glass eyes and prosthetic limbs

25:14.620 --> 25:23.460
and false teeth and so on. But ironically, it's not humans who conceive of the
cyborg, but machines. To save man from himself, computers all over the world

25:23.460 --> 25:33.560
link up to form an artificial intelligence. Too far out? Not necessarily, says
Pohl. It's a 50-50 chance, in my opinion, whether machine intelligence can ever

25:33.560 --> 25:46.400
develop these sort of independent, self-defining goals that human beings can't.
But I don't think it's impossible. It's just that machines have not yet got that

25:46.400 --> 25:55.960
smart. Jem, published in 1979, also presents a chaotic world, which this time
succeeds in destroying itself. But some humans have escaped Earth. They're on

25:55.960 --> 26:03.720
another planet and have formed a fragile new society in combination with some
aliens they meet there. Pohl meant the ending to be upbeat. Well, I think that

26:03.720 --> 26:16.020
it's hopeful. I think that what I was trying to say in Jem was perhaps a little
more overt preaching than I usually intend. And I'm not sure that it came across

26:16.020 --> 26:25.960
the way I intended it to. But the subtitle of Jem is The Making of a Utopia. And
what I was trying to say in the novel is that you can't really plan a utopia.

26:26.220 --> 26:40.460
You cannot construct a society that will make everybody happy and productive and
glad to be alive. Because the happiness, satisfaction, productivity are not a

26:40.460 --> 26:53.960
state. They're a process. And no rigid system can survive giving people maximum
opportunities to realize their potential without being flexible and changeable.

26:54.600 --> 27:02.000
Much of Pohl's social science fiction deals with negative societies. But Pohl
says he's basically an optimist. And there's a reason for focusing on the bad

27:02.000 --> 27:13.920
side. I'm really Pollyanna. I'm a great optimist about the world. I think that
we're in for some terrible times. And I don't think that most of us will enjoy

27:13.920 --> 27:21.880
much of what happens in the next few years. But I think in the long run the
human race will straighten itself out and learn to be able to live better with

27:21.880 --> 27:32.840
each other. But as far as writing a novel is concerned, it's not too interesting
to write about a utopia. I mean, what are you going to say about a bunch of

27:32.840 --> 27:45.320
people who walk around in togas and eat whole wheat bread and never have any bad
thoughts? It's much more interesting to paint the disasters that may occur as a

27:45.320 --> 27:54.340
sort of... Well, I think it's Kingsley Amis who calls that kind of science
fiction cautionary literature. It's not saying what will happen. It's just

27:54.340 --> 27:56.380
warning what might happen if we don't watch out.

